CHAPTER XI.

1. Pro tempore] “As the occasion requircd.'' Comp. Catil. 51; Juyur. 74.

2. Justa] Scil. funera or officia. Caesar sayS, Bell. Gall. vi. 19, justis funeribus confectis; but Cicero, pro Rosc. Am. 8, paterno funeri justa solvere. So justa serre, or clare: Gr. τὰ νομιζόμενας Festus, in voc. Praecidanea: qui mortuo justa non fecisset, id est, glebam non objecisset.

3. Regufl] ‘⁴ Petty kings,” “ chieftains‚” δύνασται. The word is not found in Cicero or Cacsar.

4. Minimus] So. natu. which is generally expressed‚ un- less filius, or ex filiis, is added, as Liv. i. 53. Sextus filius ejus qui minimus ex tribus erat. Justin. xlii. 5, obsidem Caesari minimum filium Phraatis ferens. Here ex illis, sc. refluus, means the sons> of Micipsa, who were inferior kings‚ associated in power with their father.

5. Quod apud N. ete] Comp. the story in Plutarch, Cato min. 57, of Juba assuming the place of honour between Metel- lus, Scipio and Cato. But the Romans also, at least at a later period, considered the middle the place of honour. The emperor took his seat in the senate between the consuls for the year. Hence Sil. Ital. iii. 626, of Domitian:

Tarda senectam
